    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get it. i'll make sure not to wrap the generator in a list. but i've noticed that even when i'm being careful, sometimes the memory usage just creeps up and up for no reason until the whole system slows down. it’s like the resources are being stolen or something. what causes that kind of \"hidden\" consumption?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Hidden\" consumption, or what the more experienced folk call \"memory creep,\" is often caused by things that aren't immediately obvious, like poorly managed references or objects that aren't being properly garbage collected. It's a classic case of a small, persistent piece of junk—a stray, forgotten, or overly eager-to-keep-its-stuff-around object—that keeps clinging to memory.\n\nIt's not usually the main data structure that's the culprit; it's often a reference that points back to a huge chunk of data that *should* have been released. Think of it like a tiny, sneaky goblin hiding in the corner of the room, constantly whispering to the memory, \"Hey, don't let me go!\"\n\nSometimes, this happens with closures in functions, or if you're accidentally storing large intermediate results in a global variable or a class attribute that never gets cleared. A little bit of code, like a poorly written loop that keeps creating temporary objects without letting them die, can accumulate. It's like a thousand tiny, sticky traps set up by a mischievous goblin, each one holding onto a tiny bit of memory.\n\nCheck your loops, check your function scope,",
      "source": "target",
